The paper deals with properties of metric spaces and their algorithmic applications, which are typical topics in the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The study of doubling dimension is also related to computational geometry, which falls under cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also discusses the distortion of metrics, which is a topic in information theory, hence cs.IT (Information Theory) is another likely sub-category. The use of trees in the paper suggests a connection to numerical analysis, specifically in the sub-category of cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). Finally, the paper's focus on graph-theoretic properties and their interaction with geometric properties suggests a connection to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
